MASTER OUTLINE — Hello Team Workforce Portal (Employee + Client + Admin)

A) Platform Basics
 
Three portals / roles
 
Employee portal (Hello Team Virtual Office)
 
Client portal (visibility + approvals + billing)
 
Admin portal (Hello Team operations)
 
Branding / UI
 
Must feel like a “Hello Team virtual office” for employees (warm, supportive)
 
Must feel like a “command center” for clients (clear, actionable)
 
Core goal
 
Remove manual labor
 
No emailing timesheets
 
Clients approve in portal
 
Automatic weekly invoicing + automatic charging
 
QuickBooks
 
We use QuickBooks Desktop (On-Prem) for invoicing/accounting (not QBO)
 
System must either:
 
Generate invoices inside the portal + export to QB Desktop, OR
 
Push invoices into QB Desktop via a supported integration method (developer to propose)
 
Security / Privacy
 
Employee ↔️ Hello Team support communication is private and confidential
 
Client cannot see employee communications with Hello Team
 
Audit logs
 
Any time edits, approvals, changes require logging: who/what/when/notes
 
B) Employee Portal — “Virtual Office” Experience

B1) Clock In / Clock Out (with schedule enforcement + warnings)
 
Employee clocks in/out inside portal (web + mobile-friendly)
 
Clock-in UX includes:
 
Customizable clock-in sounds (admin controlled / “play around with sounds”)
 
Employee sees:
 
Today’s schedule
 
Live timer since clock-in
 
A “shift ending” warning before end of shift
 
Clocking in early / outside schedule
 
System allows the employee to clock in early but warns them clearly using this exact meaning:
 
“You are trying to clock in before your schedule. We will allow you to do so, but please note you may not get paid for this time as it is not in your schedule. If the client does not approve it, you will only be paid for your scheduled time.”
 
Shift end warning
 
Example: “4 minutes before end of shift” notification:
 
“Your shift is ending. You will be clocked out at 5:00 PM (scheduled time). If you need to stay longer, click here to stay clocked in after your scheduled shift.”
 
If employee clicks “stay clocked in,” system prompts overtime request AND warns:
 
Overtime should ideally be requested earlier in the day
 
If requested right before shift end, it may not get approved and may not be paid
 
B2) Schedule View
 
View today schedule
 
View weekly schedule
 
View upcoming schedule changes (if any)
 
B3) Past Hours / Timesheet History (employee view)
 
View past hours by day/week
 
See breakdown: regular hours vs overtime vs unapproved overtime vs PTO/VTO
 
See statuses: approved / pending / denied
 
B4) Hello Team Support (private)
 
“Request Hello Team support” button
 
Private messaging with Hello Team (client cannot see)
 
Ability to request a call/meeting with management
 
Chat with management
 
Upload files/videos to Hello Team support thread
 
B5) Wellness / Feedback / Positive Culture
 
“How are you feeling today?” rating
 
Optional feedback text
 
Positive messages / encouragement in the portal
 
“Warm feeling of a virtual office” tone
 
B6) PTO/VTO Request System (employee-facing)
 
PTO/VTO request page(s)
 
Some clients:
 
0 PTO (PTO page hidden completely)
 
Only VTO allowed (VTO page shown)
 
Two-week notice requirement
 
PTO + VTO should normally require 2 weeks notice
 
If inside 2 weeks, system still allows request but shows a human message:
 
“This requires 2 weeks notice. Emergencies happen; you can still request it, but it may not be approved. We hope your client will understand.”
 
PTO accrual rules configurable (see Admin section)
 
Employee cannot request PTO beyond their balance
 
If insufficient PTO, system explains why and suggests VTO
 
C) Client Portal — Visibility + Approvals + Billing

C1) Client Dashboard (home)
 
See all employees assigned to them
 
“Who’s working” view:
 
Employee names
 
Clocked-in status
 
Clock-in time
 
Live counter for today
 
Weekly summary:
 
Hours worked this week (line graphs / counters)
 
Alerts panel (nag system)
 
Quick actions:
 
Approve timesheets
 
Approve/deny overtime
 
Add overtime in advance
 
Add tasks
 
Give bonus
 
Give raise
 
Payment method / billing
 
C2) Who’s Working Page (live operational view)
 
Live list of employees working now
 
Shows:
 
When they clocked in
 
Current session duration
 
Status indicators
 
C3) Timesheets Page + Approval Logic (very important)
 
Timesheet cycle: Monday → Sunday, weekly
 
Client approves in portal (no emailing)
 
Regular timesheet approval rules:
 
Client gets 24 hours to approve (you specified 24 hours here)
 
If not approved within 24 hours:
 
regular scheduled hours auto-approve
 
Client can still open timesheets later and approve any time (but regular hours will already be approved)
 
Overtime must be visually different on the timesheet
 
Different color or clearly separated section
 
Client must be able to choose:
 
“Approve entire timesheet including overtime”
 
OR “Approve timesheet but deny overtime”
 
Timesheet edits by client must require:
 
Forced “reason / note” field
 
C4) Overtime — BOTH TYPES + DISPLAY RULES

Type 1: Client Adds Overtime in Advance (scheduled OT)
 
Client can add overtime for:
 
Specific employee
 
Specific date
 
Specific time window / duration
 
This overtime is treated as “pre-approved”
 
It should show in a different color (because it was added ahead of time)
 
When time occurs, system should not display clock-out warnings or “risk” messages
 
Type 2: Employee Requests Overtime Live
 
Employee submits overtime request:
 
Amount of time
 
Date/time
 
Reason (optional but recommended)
 
Client receives:
 
SMS + email + in-app notification
 
If client approves:
 
It becomes “approved overtime”
 
System should not show “clock out” warnings
 
It appears on timesheets as approved overtime
 
Late overtime request near shift end (risk logic)
 
If request is made right before shift ends:
 
System should warn employee there is risk it won’t be approved and may not be paid
 
System behavior needs to “tie beautifully into timesheets + billing”
 
Overtime that is not approved:
 
Cannot be billed
 
Needs heavy pressure/notifications to client to approve/deny
 
D) Billing + Payment System (Auto-charge, robust, pressure if declined)

D1) Billing Cycle
 
Billing is weekly (every 7 days)
 
System generates invoice automatically weekly based on:
 
Approved regular hours
 
Approved overtime
 
Any adjustments/edits that were approved
 
D2) Payment Methods
 
Client can store:
 
Credit card
 
ACH
 
Multiple cards/bank accounts (as many as they like)
 
Each time they add a method:
 
System performs authorization/verification to confirm it works
 
Terms & conditions acceptance:
 
Client must agree to automatic weekly charges
 
D3) Auto Charging
 
When invoice issues:
 
Card/ACH is charged automatically
 
Client receives email with:
 
PDF invoice
 
Receipt
 
Billing history page:
 
Invoice list
 
Status: paid / unpaid / declined / pending
 
Download PDFs anytime
 
D4) Declined Card / Failed ACH (pressure + lockouts)
 
If payment fails:
 
“Harassment-level” reminders (your words) via SMS/email/in-app until updated
 
If they do not update payment method:
 
Employee should not be able to clock in
 
When client uploads new card:
 
System automatically charges all unpaid invoices immediately
 
Must be clean, secure, and reliable
 
E) Payroll Pressure System (8th/22nd + manual overrides for holidays)

E1) Payroll Dates
 
Payroll is twice monthly:
 
8th
 
22nd
 
Sometimes payroll date moves earlier (ex: before Jewish holiday)
 
Admin must be able to override payroll schedule and trigger notifications early
 
E2) Payroll Reminder for UNAPPROVED OVERTIME
 
Overtime not approved should generate pressure in two places:
 
Before weekly billing closes (2 days window)
 
Before payroll pays out (8th/22nd), especially overtime from prior billing cycles
 
E3) Weekly Billing Close Pressure (2-day push)
 
Beginning 2 days before billing closes:
 
Client gets SMS/email/in-app alerts:
 
“Hi, your account will be charged for your employee (name). There is overtime that is not approved. Please click here to approve or deny the overtime before your account is billed so the employee can get paid for approved hours.”
 
If client ignores:
 
Regular time still bills automatically
 
Overtime remains unbilled/unpaid until approved
 
E4) Payroll-Day “Global Push” Button (Admin-triggered)
 
Admin button to send a broadcast notification to all clients who have unapproved overtime (from previous billing cycles between 8th and 22nd)
 
Message meaning:
 
“Your employee will be paid tomorrow. We see overtime not approved. If you do not approve it, they will NOT get paid for that time.”
 
Professional tone (not “sad” wording but same concept)
 
